name: Goat
description: Goat Format is the first GX era format and one of the most popular retro Yu-Gi-Oh! TCG formats. The latest core sets are Flaming Eternity (FET) and The Lost Millennium (TLM). Notable additions include Rescue Cat, Brain Control, and Lightning Vortex. Confiscation and The Forceful Sentry are now Forbidden, while Delinquent Duo and Graceful Charity are unbanned. The format’s name comes from the historically successful Goat Control deck, however, the modern metagame revolves around Chaos Turbo. The format is simple and interactive, requiring players to use skills such as reading, bluffing, and resource management.

name: Edison
description: Edison is a 5D’s era format and one of the most popular retro Yu-Gi-Oh! TCG formats, backed by strong community support. Since Lightsworn Format, only Starlight Road was introduced.  The format’s name comes from the 75th Shonen Jump Championship held in Edison, New Jersey, which was won by Jeff Jones’s iconic Quickdraw Plant deck. The modern metagame is dominated by Blackwing, HERO, and Frog variants, with other decks and engines such as Dragon, Fairy, Lightsworn, Machina, Plant, and Zombie being competitive. Edison is well known for its open-ended deck-building and highly diverse metagame.

name: Tengu
description: Tengu Plant is the first Zexal era format and one of the more popular retro Yu-Gi-Oh! formats. The latest core set available is Generation Force (GENF). This format’s name comes from the iconic Synchro Plant deck that uses Reborn Tengu and Plant Tuners to make a variety of Synchro monsters, including the very powerful Trishula, Dragon of the Ice Barrier. While the Plant deck dominated historically, many other decks are extremely competitive in the modern metagame, including Agent, T.G. Stun, Hero Beat, and several Chaos variants.

name: Wind-Up
description: Wind-Up is a Zexal era format and recently became one of the more popular retro Yu-Gi-Oh! formats. Some players call the format “REDU Format” because the latest core set available is Return of the Duelist (REDU). The most notable addition is the Geargia archetype. This format’s name comes from the iconic Wind-Up deck that emerged from the banlist with a lower ceiling (no hand loop) but similar consistency. While the Wind-Up deck is quite strong, many other decks are competitive in the modern metagame, including Dark World, Chaos Dragon, Geargia, Dino Rabbit, and Hero variants.

name: HAT
description: HAT Format is the final Zexal era format and one of the more popular retro Yu-Gi-Oh! TCG formats, backed by strong community support. The format’s name comes from the Hand, Artifact, and Traptrix engines. Since Vegas Format, Dragons of Legend (DRLG) and Primal Origin (PRIO) were introduced. Notable additions include Traptrix Dionaea, Soul Charge, Sylvan support, and the Artifact and Hand archetypes. The modern metagame features diverse decks including Artifact Traptrix, Bujin, Geargia, Mermail, and Spellbook. This was the last format before Pendulum Monsters and the removal of First Turn Draw.

name: Reaper
description: Reaper Forat is a GX era format shaped by an aggressive ban list that hit Goat Control and Combo decks. The latest core sets are Elemental Energy (EEN) and Shadow of Infinity (SOI). Notable additions include Treeborn Frog, Pot of Avarice, and the Dark World archetype. Delinquent Duo, Graceful Charity, and Pot of Greed are now Forbidden. The “good” Last Will ruling is in effect, which is a major boost to the Stein Monarch deck.

name: Yugi-Kaiba
description: Yugi-Kaiba Format is the first Yu-Gi-Oh! TCG format, including Legend of Blue-Eyes White Dragon (LOB) and Starter Decks Yugi (SDY) and Kaiba (SDK). There are a few Effect Monsters, power Spells, and simple Monster removal. Battle Phase dynamics are important, with cards like Trap Hole and Reinforcements to consider. This is Yu-Gi-Oh! in its simplest form.

name: Critter
description: Critter Format, named after the OCG's Sangan, is the second Yu-Gi-Oh! TCG format. The latest core set is Metal Raiders (MRD). Notable additions include many new Effect Monsters, Heavy Storm, and Mirror Force. For the first time, we see a clear split in play-styles between Aggro and Control. Players can also set up win conditions via OTKs with cards like Cannon Soldier.

name: Treasure
description: Treasure Format, named after the OCG's hand-disruption Spells, is a DM era format that predates the first banlist. The latest core set is Magic Ruler (MRL). Notable additions include the hand-disruption Spells, Mystical Space Typhoon, Painful Choice, recruiter Monsters, and Ritual Monsters. The hand-disruption Spells put a premium on going first and efficient deck-building.

name: Imperial
description: Imperial Format is a DM era format that predates the first banlist. The latest core set is Pharaoh’s Servant (PSV). Notable additions include Jinzo, Nobleman of Crossout, Premature Burial, Call of the Haunted, and Imperial Order. This format introduces the game’s first good counter to power Spells in Imperial Order and its first true boss Monster in Jinzo.

name: Android
description: Android Format, named after the OCG's Jinzo, is a DM era format that predates the first banlist. The latest core set is Labyrinth of Nightmare (LON). Notable additions include Gemini Elf, Bazoo the Soul-Eater, Kycoo the Ghost Destroyer, Skull Lair, and Torrential Tribute. Due to mistranslations, cards such as Skull Lair can banish any card from the Graveyard.

name: Joey-Pegasus
description: Joey-Pegasus Format is a DM era format that predates the first banlist. The latest cards come from Starter Decks Joey (SDJ) and Pegasus (SDP). Notable additions include Graceful Charity, Sinister Serpent, Scapegoat, and Harpie’s Feather Duster. This is one of the only formats to feature two legal copies of Graceful Charity.

name: Fiber
description: Fiber Format is a DM era format that predates the first banlist. The latest core set is Legacy of Darkness (LOD). Notable additions include Exiled Force, Fiber Jar, Injection Fairy Lily, Yata-Garasu and Reinforcement of the Army. These cards create interesting new dynamics between card advantage and life points, particularly with Fiber Jar's ability to reset the game.

name: Yata
description: Yata Format is a DM era format that predates the first banlist. The latest core set is Pharaonic Guardian (PGD). Notable additions include Don Zaloog, Spirit Reaper, Mirage of Nightmare, Ring of Destruction, and the Gravekeeper archetype. Historically, games often ended in "Yata locks", with Yata-Garasu forcing the opponent to skip their Draw Phase every turn.

name: Scientist
description: Scientist Format is a DM era format that predates the first ban list. The latest core set is Magician’s Force (MFC). Notable additions include Breaker the Magical Warrior, Magical Scientist, Tribe-Infecting Virus, and Royal Decree. This is the only format in the history of the TCG with 3 legal copies of Magical Scientist, and thus Scientist FTK is quite potent here.

name: Vampire
description: Vampire Format is a DM era format that predates the first banlist. The latest core set is Dark Crisis (DCR). Notable additions include D.D. Warrior Lady, Vampire Lord, Butterfly Dagger - Elma, and Skill Drain. Magical Scientist is now Limited. Warrior Control mostly replaces Tomato Control, and Zombie becomes a viable rogue deck.

name: Chaos
description: Chaos Format is a DM era format that predates the first banlist. The latest core set is Invasion of Chaos (IOC). The format revolves around special summoning two of the most iconic cards ever printed, Black Luster Soldier - Envoy of the Beginning and Chaos Emperor Dragon - Envoy of the End, by banishing a LIGHT and a DARK monster from your Graveyard. Other notable additions include Chaos Sorcerer, Dark Magician of Chaos, and Dimension Fusion.

name: Warrior
description: Warrior Format is the final DM era format and the first to feature a banlist. The latest core sets are Ancient Sanctuary (AST), Soul of the Duelist (SOD), and Rise of Destiny (ROD). Notable additions include D.D. Assailant, Monarchs, and Monster Gate. A consequential banlist change is that Chaos Emperor Dragon - Envoy of the End is now Forbidden. The format’s name comes from the historically successful Warrior Control deck, though the modern metagame is quite diverse. During this format, the Shonen Jump Championship series began, with Metagame.com providing live-coverage to a global audience.

name: Cyber
description: Cyber Format is a GX era format that shares a banlist with Goat Format. The latest core set is Cybernetic Revolution (CRV), a set that changed the nature of the game. Notable additions include Cyber Dragon, Cyber End Dragon, and Cyber Twin Dragon. Cyber Dragon sets a new bar for beaters, and the Cyber Dragon Fusion Monsters unlock the full potential of cards like Cyber-Stein and Metamorphosis. The format largely regarded as a more explosive version of Goat Format.

name: Chaos Return
description: Chaos Return is a GX era format shaped by the return of Graceful Charity and a second Magician of Faith, ushering in a brief period of slower gameplay. Since Reaper Format, Enemy of Justice (EOJ) was introduced, while Dark Hole was Forbidden, and Treeborn Frog and Last Will were Limited. Notable additions include Banisher of the Radiance, Dimensional Fissure, and Macro Cosmos. The format was historically dominated by Chaos decks, most memorably, Chaos Return. As the metagame developed, Chaos Recruiter and Chaos Control decks featuring Royal Decree began to emerge.

name: Stein
description: Stein is a GX era format shaped by an aggressive ban of Chaos Sorcerer, which was previously Unlimited. Since Chaos Return Format, Power of the Duelist (POTD) and Cyberdark Impact (CDIP) were introduced, while Thousand-Eyes Restrict was Forbidden. Notable additions include Chimeratech Overdragon, Future Fusion, Overload Fusion, Chain Strike, and Accumulated Fortune. Now that the “Age of Chaos” had officially come to a close, the format was dominated by decks featuring Cyber-Stein, Monarchs, and Burn strategies.

name: Chimeratech
description: Chimeratech is a GX era format defined by the game’s first “emergency ban”, which hit Cyber-Stein. Since Stein Format, Structure Deck: Machine Re-Volt (SD10) was introduced. Notable additions include Green Gadget, Red Gadget, Yellow Gadget, and support for the Ancient Gear archetype. In the only premier event of the format, Machine OTK decks focused on summoning Chimeratech Overdragon were dominant, but the modern metagame appears to be more diverse.

name: Demise
description: Demise is a GX era format known for its explosive gameplay and open-ended deck building, and it’s very similar to the next format, Trooper. Since Airblade Format, Strike of Neos (STON) was introduced, while Graceful Charity was Forbidden, and Dimension Fusion and Giant Trunade were Limited. Notable additions include D.D. Crow, Advanced Ritual Art, Pulling the Rug, and the Six Samurai archetype.

name: Trooper
description: Trooper is a GX era format known for its explosive gameplay and open-ended deck building. Since Demise Format, Force of the Breaker (FOTB) was introduced, while Magical Stone Excavation was “emergency” Limited. Notable additions include Raiza the Storm Monarch, Green Baboon, Defender of the Forest, and the Volcanic archetype. The format was defined by the Destiny HERO engine and the Card Trooper + Machine Duplication combo. It was the final format to feature pre-errata Brain Control and Trap Dustshoot at 3 copies.

name: Zombie
description: Zombie is a GX era format shaped by a dampening of the game’s explosiveness via an aggressive banlist. Since Trooper Format, Tactical Evolution (TAEV) was introduced, while Snatch Steal and Ring of Destruction were Forbidden, and Card Trooper, Brain Control, and Trap Dustshoot were Limited. Notable additions include Elemental HERO Neos Alius, Il Blud, Zombie Master, and Dark Bribe. The metagame was quite diverse, with many decks being able to compete. Notably, the Zombie deck was arguably Tier 1 for the first time, despite several attempts to support it since Pharaonic Guardian.

name: Perfect Circle
description: Perfect Circle is a GX era format known for its methodical gameplay. Since Zombie Format, Gladiator’s Assault (GLAS) and Structure Deck: Rise of the Dragon Lords (SDRL) were introduced. Notable additions include Light and Darkness Dragon, Foolish Burial, Trade-In, Dimensional Prison, and the Gladiator Beast archetype. The metagame is centralized around the Perfect Circle Monarch deck, which uses the Destiny Hero engine combined with Raiza the Storm Monarch and Light and Darkness Dragon to control the game.

name: DAD Return
description: DAD Return is a GX era format known for its explosive gameplay. Since Perfect Circle Format, Phantom Darkness (PTDN), a set that changed the nature of the game, has been introduced. Notable additions include Dark Armed Dragon, Allure of Darkness, Dark Grepher, Cyber Valley, and Caius the Shadow Monarch, while Monster Reborn was unbanned. The metagame revolves around the infamous DAD Return deck, which uses Dark Armed Dragon, Dimension Fusion, and Return from the Different Dimension to make explosive pushes.

name: Gladiator
description: Gladiator Format is the final GX era format and it’s defined by the “emergency ban” of Dimension Fusion and the “emergency limit” of Return from the Different Dimension. Since DAD Return, Light of Destruction (LODT) was introduced. Notable additions include the Lightsworn archetype, Honest, Gladiator Beast Gyzarus, Substitoad, and Fossil Dyna. The metagame revolves around the near full-power Gladiator Beast deck, which has access to 3 copies of Cold Wave and 3 copies of Gladiator Beast Bestiari.
